page.text: The purpose of this Safety Study is to identify crash problems, determine site-specific
countermeasures, and set up reasonable time periods to implement the proposed
countermeasures along US 322 (Mayfield Road) from Maple Road to Daytona Road in the cities
of Cleveland Heights, South Euclid, and Lyndhurst. More specifically, this report is structured to
address the recent crash history (372 crashes from 2007 through 2009) and to provide
recommendations to alleviate crashes associated with the high rate of rear end, angle, and
This section of US 322 (log point 8.26 – 10.28) has been identified by the Ohio Department of
Transportation as a top crash location in the state based on total crashes, average daily traffic
(ADT), relative change in crashes over time, and crash severity from 2007 – 2009. Specifically,
this section ranked #141 (the lower the number, the higher the priority) on ODOT’s 2009
Highway Safety Program List for non-freeway locations and exhibits a high rate of injury crashes
(about 1 in 4 crashes resulted in an injury). Also, this section ranked #44 on ODOT’s 2009 Hot
Spot List for non-freeway locations. The most recent three years of available crash data (2007 –
2009) will be used for this report.

The study section of US 322 (locally known as Mayfield Road) is located in the cities of
Cleveland Heights, South Euclid, and Lyndhurst all within Cuyahoga County, Ohio. The study
limits are from log point 8.26 (Maple Road) to log point 10.28 (Clubside Road). US 322 runs
east to west and is composed of a five lane cross section throughout (two eastbound lanes, two
westbound lanes, and a center left turn lane). Based on ODOT’s Traffic Survey Report from
2010, this section has an ADT of approximately 19,080 vehicles per day including approximately
US 322 is primarily residential from Maple Road to Ardoon Street/Middleton Road, heavily
commercial from Ardoon Street/Middleton Road to Dill Road, and again residential from Dill
Road to Daytona Road. The major crossroads are Warrensville Center Road, South Belvoir
Boulevard, and South Green Road. US 322 is classified as an urban principal arterial as is
Warrrensville Center Road. South Green is classified as an urban minor arterial and South
Belvoir is classified as an urban collector. Signalized intersections and their respective
Traffic control is span wire supported in Cleveland Heights and mast arm supported elsewhere.

page.text: DLZ received crash data from ODOT. Data was verified by location and type utilizing OH-1
reports provided. The most recent three years of data available (2007 – 2009) was analyzed for
crash trends and safety issues. Table 1 summarizes the crash data.
Based on crash data obtained from ODOT, the most common type of crash on US 322 was the
rear end crash. Between 2007 and 2009, 191 rear end crashes occurred at the study
intersection (accounting for over 50% of all crashes), forty four of which caused an injury. Rear
end crashes occurred largely at intersection locations – most frequently on approaches of
The second most frequently occurring crash from 2007 to 2009 within the study section was the
angle crash. Seventy eight angle crashes accounted for about 20% of all crashes. Angle crashes
most frequently occurred at drive locations when a vehicle pulled out of a drive onto US 322 or
one of the cross streets within the study area. Of the approximately thirty angle crashes that
did occur at intersections, eighteen were caused by red light running. Eight angle crashes

DLZ observed the intersection on several occasions in late March and early April 2011.
Observations were made for AM, midday, and PM peak hours. Although volumes are heavy all
day, the PM peak hour contains the highest vehicular and pedestrian volumes. Notable queues
in the PM were observed at US 322 and Warrensville Center Road in the eastbound direction
(extending west to Noble Road) and in the westbound direction (extending just west of Winston
Road/Holmden Road). In addition, PM queues were observed at US 322 and South Green Road
in the eastbound direction (extending west of Victory Drive).

along US 322 in Cleveland Heights (Ardoon/Middleton, Noble, and Warrensville Center) are in

Based on field observations, crash data, and analysis of the study section, there are several
improvements that can be made to potentially reduce crashes and increase safety. Proposed
countermeasures at the top crash locations – as described in Section 4.0 Crash Analysis – are
Noble Road to Brookline Road/Genesee Road, including Warrensville Center Road
(approximately 100 crashes) – This portion of US 322 had the most crashes as well as
the highest injury per crash rate. Crashes break down as follows:
The primary crash type is rear end crashes, which based on crash reports and field
observations is likely caused by congestion on US 322. Although the Noble Road and
Warrensville Center Road signals are in coordination, the next signal to the east
(Winston Road/Holmden Road) is not. Traffic does not progress well through this area
and conditions are made worse by the number of driveways in addition to the
unsignalized intersections with Brookline Road and Genesee Road. Eastbound queues
at Warrensville Center Road were observed past Noble Road and westbound queues
were observed to approach Winston Road/Holmden Road.
DLZ recommends coordinating signals across the border of Cleveland Heights and South
Euclid to create one in-sync system. This can be accomplished through the use of GPS
clocks in each of the signal system’s master controller. As a short-term
countermeasure, DLZ recommends relamping signals with LED indications and adding
black backplates with yellow retroreflective strips to increase signal visibility. Also as
noted above in a previous section, lane use signs are only provided for the northbound
and westbound approaches. DLZ recommends lane use signs at the intersection and
approximately 250 feet back from the intersection on the southbound and eastbound
approaches. Advance lane use signs not only help drivers get into the correct lane, they
also make drivers aware of the upcoming intersection.
The second most prevalent crash in this area was the angle crash. Most angle crashes
occurred at intersections and the highest concentration occurred at Brookline Road.
Eight crashes occurred when a southbound vehicle pulled out of Brookline Road into
oncoming westbound traffic. Based on OH-1 crash reports, the primary cause was
westbound queues blocking sight distance of the driver on Brookline Road.
Consideration should be given to making Brookline Road right-out only or right-in, right-
out. Also, consideration should be given to consolidating or eliminating drives on all
four corners to provide better access management.
Sheffield Road to Dean Drive including South Green Road and Victory Drive
(approximately 85 crashes) – Crashes for this portion of US 322 break down as follows:
The primary crash in this section was rear end crashes which again points to congestion.
Sheffield Road and Victory Drive are about 600 feet apart and Victory Drive is only about
350 feet from South Green Road. AM and PM peak observations revealed that US 322
eastbond queues at South Green Road extend through Victory Drive and westbound
queues extend past Dean Drive. DLZ’s recommendation is to continue signal
coordination through this section. Furthermore, consider LED indications and
backplates. Overhead lane use signs are utilized northbound and southbound on South
Green Road and eastbound on US 322. Consider installing lane use signs for the
Eighteen angle crashes occurred in the section, eleven of which were at drive locations.
The main area of concern are the drives just east of South Green on US 322. Citing OH-1
crash reports, crashes generally occurred when queues were present on US 322 from
South Green Road. Two likely scenarios that led to these crashes are a driver’s sight was
obstructed from queued vehicles or a driver became impatient with long queues and
minimum gaps to enter US 322. Access management strategies should be considered in
this section to consolidate or eliminate drives that pose a potential safety threat or
restrict movements, specifically the left-out movement.
Argonne Road to Francis Court including South Belvoir Boulevard (approximately 60
crashes) – Crashes for this section of US 322 break down as follows:
The primary crash in this section was the rear end crash. As in the other two sections,
rear end crashes appear to be linked to the congestion in this corridor. DLZ’s
recommendation holds for this section – coordinate the signals along US 322. Also,
consider LED indications and backplates to improve visibility.
Angle crashes were also numerous in this section and primarily occurred at drive
locations. DLZ recommends access management strategies which may include
Although there were no head-on crashes on South Belvoir Boulevard, the roadway
consists of raised medians for both northbound and southbound traffic just outside of
US 322. DLZ recommends providing increased visibility of the median to provide
guidance for traffic – especially left-turning traffic – such as installing the “keep right”
R4-7 sign with sign post reflector. See the photos below.
There are a number of recommendations that apply to the entire study area. First, DLZ
examined yellow and all-red times and compared existing timings to recommended timings
from the Institute of Transportation Engineers (ITE). Inadequate change and clearance intervals
may impact the number of angle crashes within the intersection as well as rear end crashes.
DLZ recommends considering revising signal timings to meet ITE recommended clearance
intervals, however an analysis of the coordinated sections should be conducted first to ensure
that increasing yellow and all read times (and therefore decreasing available green time) is not
detrimental to the system as a whole.
Due to the high number of rear end crashes, DLZ recommends additional signal heads to
increase signal visibility. Currently, all signalized intersections have two signal heads. Consider
adding a third signal head to eastbound and westbound approaches on US 322 for all signalized

For pedestrians, Walk and Flashing Don’t Walk (FDW) intervals were examined for the major
intersections. The results are presented on the next page.
All walk times are sufficient, however DLZ recommends increasing FDW times at Belvoir
Boulevard and South Green Road based on a 3.5 foot/second walking pace.
